Once the funeral gathering broke up, the men dispersed,\uc0\u8232 each one going to his own ship, concerned to eat\u8232 and then enjoy sweet sleep. But Achilles kept on weeping,\u8232 remembering his dear companion. All-conquering Sleep\u8232 could not overcome him, as he tossed and turned,\u8232 longing for manly, courageous, strong Patroclus,\u8232 thinking of all he\'92d done with him, all the pain\u8232 they\'92d suffered, as they\'92d gone through wars with other men\u8232 and with the perilous sea. As he kept remembering,\u8232 he cried heavy tears, sometimes lying on his side,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\u8232 sometimes on his back or on his face. Then he\'92d get up,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 to wander in distress, back and forth along the shore.\u8232 He\'92d see Dawn\'92s approach across the sea and beaches,\u8232 then he\'92d harness his fast horses to their chariot,\u8232 tie on Hector and drag him behind, driving\u8232 three times around the tomb of Menoetius\'92 dead son.\u8232 Then in his hut he\'92d rest again, leaving Hector\u8232 stretched out, face down in the dust. But Apollo,\u8232 feeling pity for Hector, though he was dead,\u8232 guarded his skin from any lacerations,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\u8232 covering his whole body with the golden aegis,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 so as Achilles dragged him, he did not tear his skin.\u8232 Still Achilles kept dishonouring godlike Hector.\
Then the blessed gods, looking on, pitied Hector.\uc0\u8232 So they urged keen-eyed Hermes, killer of Argus,\u8232 to steal the corpse, an idea that pleased them all,\u8232 except for Hera, Poseidon, and Athena,\u8232 the girl with glittering eyes, who kept up the hatred\u8232 they\'92d felt when they first started to loathe Ilion,\u8232 Priam and his people, for Alexander\'92s folly\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 he\'92d been contemptuous of those goddesses,\u8232 when they were visiting his sheep-fold, choosing\u8232 the one who volunteered to serve his dangerous lust.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://records.viu.ca/~johnstoi/homer/iliad24.htm#n1"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \strokec2 *}}\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\uc0\u8232 But after the twelfth dawn had come since Hector\'92s death,\u8232 Phoebus Apollo spoke out to the immortals:\
\'93You gods are cruel and vindictive.\uc0\u8232 Did Hector never sacrifice to you,\u8232 burning thighs of perfect bulls and goats?\u8232 And can\'92t you now rouse yourself to save him,\u8232 though he\'92s a corpse, for his wife, his mother,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\u8232 and his child to look at, and for Priam, too,\u8232 his father, and the people, who\'92d burn him\u8232 with all speed and give him burial rites?\u8232 No, you want to help ruthless Achilles,\u8232 whose heart has no restraint. In that chest\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 his mind cannot be changed. Like some lion,\u8232 he thinks savage thoughts, a beast which follows\u8232 only its own power, its own proud heart,\u8232 as it goes out against men\'92s flocks, seeking\u8232 a feast of cattle\'97that\'92s how Achilles\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 destroys compassion. And in his heart\u8232 there\'92s no sense of shame, which can help a man\u8232 or harm him. No doubt, a man can suffer loss\u8232 of someone even closer than a friend\'97\u8232 a brother born from the same mother\u8232 or even a son. He pays his tribute\u8232 with his tears and his laments\'97then stops.\u8232 For Fates have put in men resilient hearts.\u8232 But this man here, once he took Hector\'92s life,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 ties him behind his chariot, then drags him\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\u8232 around his dear companion\'92s burial mound.\u8232 He\'92s done nothing to help or honour him.\u8232 He should take care he doesn\'92t anger us.\u8232 Though he\'92s a fine man, in this rage of his\u8232 he\'92s harming senseless dust.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Then Hera,\uc0\u8232 angry at Apollo, replied\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Lord of the silver bow,\uc0\u8232 yes, indeed, what you say may well be true,\u8232 if you gods give Hector and Achilles\u8232 equal worth. But Hector is a mortal man,\u8232 suckled at a woman\'92s breast, while Achilles\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\u8232 is the child of a goddess I raised myself.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 I brought her up and gave her to Peleus\u8232 to be his wife, a man dear to the hearts\u8232 of the immortal gods. All of you were there,\u8232 when they got married. You, too, were with us\u8232 at the banquet, you friend of evil men,\u8232 clutching your lyre, as slippery as ever.\'94\
Cloud gatherer Zeus then answered Hera, saying:\
\'93Hera, don\'92t get so angry with the gods.\uc0\u8232 These two will not both share equal honours.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 Still, of all mortal men in Ilion,\u8232 Hector was the favourite of the gods.\u8232 At least that\'92s what he was to me.\u8232 He never failed to offer me fine gifts.\u8232 At their communal feasts, my own altar\u8232 never went without the proper offerings,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 libations and sacrificial smoke,\u8232 as is our right. But we\'92ll not let this corpse,\u8232 brave Hector\'92s body, be taken secretly.\u8232 Achilles would for certain learn of it,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 since his mother sees him all the time,\u8232 both day and night. But one of the gods\u8232 should tell Thetis to come here before me,\u8232 so I can put a useful plan to her,\u8232 how Achilles can get gifts from Priam\u8232 and then give Hector back to him.\'94\
Once Zeus had spoken, storm-swift Iris rushed away,\uc0\u8232 bearing Zeus\'92 message. Half way between Samos\u8232 and rocky Imbros she plunged into the sea.\u8232 As waters roared above her, she sank way down,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\u8232 just as a plummet sinks when fastened to a lure,\u8232 one fashioned out of horn from some farmyard ox\u8232 to bring death to hungry fish. She met Thetis\u8232 sitting in a hollow cave with other sea gods\u8232 thronging there around her. In the middle of them all,\u8232 Thetis was lamenting the fate of her fine son,\u8232 who would die in fertile Troy, far from his home.\u8232 Standing right beside her, swift-footed Iris spoke:\
\'93Rouse yourself, Thetis. Zeus, whose thoughts\uc0\u8232 endure forever, is calling for you.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\
Silver-footed Thetis then said in reply:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Why is that mighty god now summoning me?\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\uc0\u8232 I\'92m ashamed to associate with immortals,\u8232 my heart holds such immeasurable grief.\u8232 But I\'92ll go. And no matter what he says,\u8232 his words will not be wasted.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Saying this,\uc0\u8232 Thetis, queen of goddesses, took a dark veil,\u8232 the blackest of her garments, then set off on her way.\u8232 Swift Iris, with feet like wind, went on ahead.\u8232 The surging sea parted round the two of them.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 When they emerged on shore, they raced on up to heaven.\u8232 They found the wide-seeing son of Cronos in the midst\u8232 of all the other blessed gods, who live forever.\u8232 Once Athena had made room for her, Thetis sat\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\u8232 with Father Zeus. Hera placed a gold cup in her hand,\u8232 with words of welcome. She drank, then handed back the cup.\u8232 The father of the gods and men spoke first:\
\'93You\'92ve come here to Olympus, goddess Thetis,\uc0\u8232 though you\'92re grieving, with endless sorrows\u8232 in your heart. I know that. But even so,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 I\'92ll tell you the reason why I\'92ve called you here.\u8232 For nine days immortals have been quarrelling\u8232 about Achilles, sacker of cities,\u8232 and Hector\'92s corpse. They keep urging Hermes,\u8232 keen-eyed killer of Argus, to steal the body.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\u8232 But I want to give honour to Achilles,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 maintain my respect for you in future,\u8232 and keep our friendship. So you must leave quickly.\u8232 Go to the army. Tell your son what I say.\u8232 Tell him the gods are annoyed at him,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 that of all immortals I\'92m especially angry,\u8232 because, in his heartfelt fury, he keeps\u8232 Hector at his beaked ships, won\'92t give him back.\u8232 Through fear of me, he may hand Hector over.\u8232 I\'92ll also send Iris to great-hearted Priam,\u8232 telling him to go to the Achaean ships,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 to beg for his dear son, bearing presents\u8232 for Achilles to delight his heart.\'94\
Silver-footed Thetis did not disagree with Zeus.\'a0\uc0\u8232 She went speeding from Olympus\'92 peak to her son\'92s hut.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\u8232 She found him there, still mourning endlessly.\u8232 Around him, his close companions were all busy,\u8232 in a hurry to get their morning meal prepared.\u8232 Inside the hut they\'92d butchered a large woolly sheep.\u8232 His noble mother sat close by him, caressed him\u8232 with her hand, then spoke to him, saying:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93My son,\uc0\u8232 how long will you consume your heart with tears,\u8232 with this grieving, not thinking about food\u8232 or going to bed. To have sex with a woman\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\u8232 would do you good. I won\'92t see you still alive\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\u8232 much longer\'97for at this moment, Death,\u8232 your powerful fate, is standing close at hand.\u8232 But quickly, listen to me. For I\'92m here\u8232 as messenger from Zeus. He told me this\'97\u8232 the gods are angry with you. Zeus himself\u8232 is the angriest of all immortals,\u8232 because, in your heartfelt fury, you keep\u8232 Hector by your beaked ships, won\'92t return him.\u8232 So come, now. Give him back, and for that corpse\u8232 accept a ransom.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Swift-footed Achilles\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\uc0\u8232 then replied to Thetis, saying:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93So be it.\uc0\u8232 Whoever brings the ransom, let that man\u8232 have the corpse, if that\'92s what the Olympian\u8232 in his own heart truly desires.\'94\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\
