Zeus spoke. Storm-footed Iris rushed off with the message.\uc0\u8232 Reaching Priam\'92s house, she found him weeping there\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0200\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[160]\u8232 and mourning. His sons were sitting with their father\u8232 inside the courtyard, wetting garments with their tears.\u8232 The old man sat with them, cloak tightly wrapped around him.\u8232 Both his head and neck were covered with the dung\u8232 he\'92d grovelled in and grabbed up by the handful.\u8232 His daughters and sons\'92 wives were crying through the house,\u8232 thinking of many noble warriors who\'92d been killed\u8232 at Achaean hands. Zeus\'92 messenger approached.\u8232 Standing beside Priam, she spoke in a soft voice,\u8232 but nonetheless his limbs began to tremble.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0210\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[170]\
\'93Let your heart be brave, Priam, son of Dardanus.\uc0\u8232 Don\'92t be afraid. I\'92ve not come with news\u8232 of any harm to you, but to do good.\u8232 I am a messenger to you from Zeus\'97\u8232 he may be far off, but he looks out for you,\u8232 cares very much, and feels pity for you.\u8232 The Olympian is telling you to ransom\u8232 godlike Hector. Take presents to Achilles,\u8232 fine things his heart will find delightful.\u8232 You must go alone. No other Trojan man\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0220\u8232 is to go along with you. A herald,\u8232 an older man, may make the journey with you,\u8232 to drive the mules and sturdy wagon\u8232 and bring back to the city the body\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[180]\u8232 of the godlike man Achilles killed.\u8232 You mustn\'92t think of death or be afraid.\u8232 A proper escort will accompany you\'97\u8232 Hermes, killer of Argus\'97to guide you,\u8232 until he brings you to Achilles.\u8232 Once he\'92s led you to Achilles\'92 hut,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0230\u8232 that man will not kill you\'97he\'92ll restrain\u8232 all other men. For he\'92s not stupid,\u8232 blind, or disrespectful of the gods.\u8232 He\'92ll spare a suppliant, treat him kindly.\'94\
With these words, swift-footed Iris went away.\uc0\u8232 Priam told his sons to prepare a sturdy mule cart\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[190]\u8232 and lash on a wicker box. Then he went in person\u8232 down to the sweet-smelling vaulted storage chamber\u8232 lined with cedar, which held many of his treasures.\u8232 He summoned Hecuba, his wife, then said:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0240\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93My lady,\uc0\u8232 a messenger has come to me from Zeus,\u8232 instructing me to ransom our dear son.\u8232 I\'92m to go to the Achaean ships, taking\u8232 gifts for Achilles to delight his heart.\u8232 So come, tell me what you feel about this.\u8232 My own heart and spirit are urging me,\u8232 in a strange and fearful way, to go there,\u8232 to the ships and wide Achaean camp.\'94\
At Priam\'92s words, his wife cried out. Then she replied:\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[200]\
\'93Where\'92s your mind gone, that wisdom you once had,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0250\uc0\u8232 for which in earlier days you were well known\u8232 among your subjects and with strangers, too?\u8232 How can you want to visit the Achaean ships,\u8232 to go alone, before the eyes of the man\u8232 who\'92s killed so many of your noble sons?\u8232 You\'92ve an iron heart. If he captures you,\u8232 once he sees you, that man\'92s so savage,\u8232 so unreliable, he\'92ll show no pity.\u8232 He\'92ll not respect you. No, let\'92s mourn here,\u8232 in our home, sitting far away from Hector.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0260\u8232 That\'92s what mighty Fate spun out for him\u8232 when he was born, when I gave birth to him\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[210]\u8232 that swift-running dogs would devour him\u8232 far from his parents beside that powerful man.\u8232 How I wish I could rip out that man\'92s heart,\u8232 then eat it. That would be some satisfaction\u8232 for my son, who wasn\'92t playing the coward\u8232 when he killed him. No, he was standing there,\u8232 defending deep-breasted Trojan women\u8232 and Trojan men, not thinking of his safety\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0270\u8232 or running off in flight.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0The old man,\uc0\u8232 godlike Priam, then said in response to Hecuba:\
\'93I want to go. Don\'92t try to stop me.\uc0\u8232 Don\'92t be a bird of ill omen in our house.\u8232 You won\'92t convince me. If some other man,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[220]\u8232 some earthly mortal, had told me this,\u8232 a prophet who interprets sacrifices\u8232 or some priest, we\'92d think it false, reject it.\u8232 But this time I heard the goddess for myself.\u8232 I stared her in the face. So I will go.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0280\u8232 Her message won\'92t be wasted. If I\'92m fated\u8232 to die by the bronze-clad Achaeans\'92 ships,\u8232 that\'92s what I wish. Let Achilles kill me,\u8232 once I\'92ve embraced my son and satisfied\u8232 my desire to mourn.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Priam finished speaking.\uc0\u8232 Then he threw open fine lids on the storage chests.\u8232 From there he took twelve lovely robes, twelve single cloaks,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[230]\u8232 as many blankets, white coverlets, and tunics.\u8232 He brought gold, weighing out a total of ten talents,\u8232 then two gleaming tripods, four cauldrons, and a cup,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0290\u8232 a splendid one given to him by men of Thrace,\u8232 when he\'92d gone there as an envoy, a fine treasure.\u8232 Even this cup the old man didn\'92t leave at home\'97\u8232 he was so eager to pay ransom for his son.\u8232 Then Priam chased the Trojans from his courtyard,\u8232 shaming them with angry words:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Go away,\uc0\u8232 you wretches! You ought to be ashamed.\u8232 Have you nothing to cry about back home,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[240]\u8232 so you come here tormenting me like this?\u8232 Isn\'92t it enough that Zeus, Cronos\'92 son,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0300\u8232 gives me this grief, that I must lose my son,\u8232 the best one of them all? Well, you\'92ll soon find out.\u8232 Now he\'92s been killed, it will be easier\u8232 for Achaeans to kill you, too.\'a0\'a0As for me,\u8232 may I go down to Hades\'92 home, before I see\u8232 this city plundered and destroyed.\'94\
