\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Priam spoke.\uc0\u8232 Then the old man ordered his servant woman\u8232 to pour pure water on his hands. She came out,\u8232 bringing with her a basin and a water jug.\u8232 Priam washed his hands. Taking the cup from his wife,\u8232 he prayed, standing in the middle of the courtyard.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0380\u8232 Gazing up to heaven, he poured out some wine,\u8232 then spoke aloud, saying:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Father Zeus,\uc0\u8232 lord of Ida, most glorious and great,\u8232 grant that when I come to Achilles\'92 hut,\u8232 I\'92ll be welcomed kindly and with pity.\u8232 Send me a bird as omen, a swift messenger,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[310]\u8232 the one that is your favourite, the strongest.\u8232 Let it appear to my right overhead,\u8232 so, once I witness it with my own eyes,\u8232 I can have faith as I go to those ships\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0390\u8232 of the fast-riding Danaans.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0So Priam prayed.\uc0\u8232 Counsellor Zeus heard him. At once he sent an eagle,\u8232 of all flying things the surest omen, a dark one,\u8232 which people call black eagle, with wings as wide\u8232 as doors on some rich man\'92s vaulted store house,\u8232 one fitted well with bolts\'97that\'92s how wide this eagle\u8232 spread its wings on either side, appearing on the right,\u8232 speeding across the city. When they saw that bird,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[320]\u8232 they all rejoiced. Hearts in their chests felt great relief.\u8232 The old man, in a hurry, climbed in his chariot,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0400\u8232 then drove out through the gate and echoing courtyard.\u8232 In front the mules drew on the four-wheeled wagon,\u8232 led by wise Idaios. The horses came behind.\u8232 The old man kept laying on the whip, urging them\u8232 swiftly through the city. All his family followed him\u8232 in tears, as if Priam were going off to his death.\u8232 When they\'92d passed the gate and reached the plain,\u8232 his sons and sons-in-law turned back to Ilion.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[330]\u8232 But as those two men came out into the plain,\u8232 they did not go unobserved by wide-seeing Zeus.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0410\u8232 Looking down on that old man, Zeus pitied him.\u8232 At once he spoke to Hermes, his dear son:\
