\'93My husband\'97you\'92ve lost your life so young,\uc0\u8232 leaving me a widow in our home,\u8232 with our son still an infant, the child\u8232 born to you and me in our wretchedness.\u8232 I don\'92t think he\'92ll grow up to adulthood.\u8232 Before that, our city will all be destroyed.\u8232 For you, who kept watch over for us, are dead.\u8232 You used to protect our city, keeping\u8232 its noble wives and little children safe.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[730]\u8232 Now, soon enough, they\'92ll all be carried off\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0900\u8232 in hollow ships. I\'92ll be there among them.\u8232 And you, my child, you\'92ll follow with me,\u8232 to some place where you\'92ll be put to work\u8232 at menial tasks, slaving for a cruel master.\u8232 Or else some Achaean man will grab your arm\u8232 and throw you from the wall\'97a dreadful death\'97\u8232 in his anger that Hector killed his brother,\u8232 or his father, or his son. For Hector\'92s hands\u8232 made great numbers of Achaeans sink their teeth\u8232 into the broad earth. In wretched warfare,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0910\u8232 your father was not gentle. So in our city\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[740]\u8232 they now weep for him. O Hector, what sorrow,\u8232 what untold grief you\'92ve laid upon your parents.\u8232 What painful sorrows will remain for me,\u8232 especially for me. As you were dying,\u8232 you didn\'92t reach your hand out from the bed,\u8232 or give me some final words of wisdom,\u8232 something I could remember always,\u8232 night and day, as I continue my lament.\'94\
Andromache said this in tears. The women all wailed with her.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0920\uc0\u8232 Then Hecuba took her turn in leading their laments:\
\'93Hector, dearest by far of all my children,\uc0\u8232 loved by the gods, as well, when you were living.\u8232 Now, at your death, they still take care of you.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[750]\u8232 When swift Achilles took my other sons,\u8232 he\'92d ship them off across the boundless seas,\u8232 to Samos, or Imbros, or foggy Lemnos.\u8232 When his long-edged bronze took away your life,\u8232 he dragged you many times around the mound\u8232 for his comrade Patroclus, whom you killed.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0930\u8232 Yet even so, he could not revive him.\u8232 Now you lie here in our house, fresh as dew,\u8232 like someone whom Apollo of the silver bow\u8232 has just come to and killed with gentle arrows.\'94\
As she spoke, Hecuba wept. She stirred them on\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[760]\uc0\u8232 to endless lamentation. Helen was the third\u8232 to lead those women in their wailing:\
\'93Hector\'97of all my husband\'92s brothers,\uc0\u8232 you\'92re by far the dearest to my heart.\u8232 My husband is godlike Alexander,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0940\u8232 who brought me here to Troy. I wish I\'92d died\u8232 before that happened! This is the twentieth year\u8232 since I went away and left my native land,\u8232 but I\'92ve never heard a nasty word from you\u8232 or an abusive speech. In fact, if anyone\u8232 ever spoke rudely to me in the house\'97\u8232 one of your brothers or sisters, some brother\'92s\u8232 well-dressed wife, or your mother\'97for your father\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[770]\u8232 always was so kind, as if he were my own\'97\u8232 you\'92d speak out, persuading them to stop,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0950\u8232 using your gentleness, your soothing words.\u8232 Now I weep for you and for my wretched self,\u8232 so sick at heart, for there\'92s no one else\u8232 in spacious Troy who\'92s kind to me and friendly.\u8232 They all look at me and shudder with disgust.\'94\
Helen spoke in tears. The huge crowd joined in their lament.\uc0\u8232 Then old Priam addressed his people:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93You Trojans,\uc0\u8232 you must fetch some wood here to the city.\u8232 Don\'92t let your hearts fear any ambush,\u8232 some crafty Achaean trick. For Achilles,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0960\u8232 when he sent me back from the hollow ships,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[780]\u8232 gave me his word they\'92d not harm us\u8232 until the twelfth day dawns.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Priam finished.\uc0\u8232 The people hitched up mules and oxen to their wagons\u8232 and then gathered before the city with all speed.\u8232 For nine days they brought in wood, an immense amount.\u8232 When the tenth dawn came, they brought brave Hector out,\u8232 then, all in tears, laid his corpse on top the funeral pyre.\u8232 They set it alight. When rose-fingered Dawn came up,\u8232 they gathered around that pyre of glorious Hector.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0970\u8232 Once they\'92d all assembled there together,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[790]\u8232 first they doused the pyre with gleaming wine, every part\u8232 that fire\'92s strength had touched. His brothers and comrades\u8232 collected Hector\'92s ash-white bones, as they mourned him\'97\u8232 heavy tears running down their cheeks\'97and placed them\u8232 in a golden urn, wrapped in soft purple cloth.\u8232 They quickly set the urn down in a shallow grave,\u8232 covered it with large stones set close together,\u8232 then hurried to pile up the mound, posting sentries\u8232 on every side, in case well-armed Achaeans\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0980\u8232 attacked too soon. Once they\'92d piled up the mound,\u8232 they went back in, gathered together for a splendid feast,\u8232 all in due order, in Priam\'92s house, king raised by Zeus.\u8232 And thus they buried Hector, tamer of horses.\
